{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215874224,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca521dab001clSpNLoV21ad5L","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_VkxpU4nLD0EEfHDciAak7hJs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\n3: description: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n7: \n8: Comprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: ### Core Principle\n16: \n17: OpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n18: \n19: ### Purpose\n20: \n21: Provide a single-source reference for the OpenCode CLI surface — every subcommand cli-opencode invokes, every flag it pins, every agent it can route to, the version baseline it is built against, and the error envelopes that need explicit recovery.\n22: \n23: ### When to Use\n24: \n25: - Looking up an OpenCode CLI subcommand or flag during a delegation\n26: - Selecting a model + variant + agent for a dispatch\n27: - Confirming the version baseline before pinning a flag set\n28: - Troubleshooting a failed `opencode run` invocation\n29: - Confirming the self-invocation guard signal against the live binary\n30: \n31: ### Key Sources\n32: \n33: | Source | URL |\n34: |--------|-----|\n35: | **Binary** | `$(command -v opencode)` (typically `~/.superset/bin/opencode` or another local bin path) |\n36: | **Repository** | https://github.com/sst/opencode |\n37: | **Version baseline** | v1.3.17 (pinned in this reference) |\n38: | **Runtime** | Node.js 18+ for the npm install path; standalone binary on macOS |\n39: \n40: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n41: \n42: <!-- ANCHOR:installation -->\n43: ## 2. INSTALLATION\n44: \n45: | Method | Command | Notes |\n46: |--------|---------|-------|\n47: | **Standalone** | `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install \\| bash` | macOS / Linux installer |\n48: | **Homebrew** | `brew install opencode` | macOS package manager |\n49: | **npm global** | `npm install -g opencode-ai` | Cross-platform when Node.js 18+ is present |\n50: | **Upgrade** | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Pin a specific version with the `target` argument |\n51: | **Uninstall** | `opencode uninstall` | Removes the binary and related state |\n52: \n53: After installation, run `opencode --version` to confirm. The cli-opencode skill is pinned to v1.3.17. Newer binaries may add or rename flags — consult Section 9 (Version Drift) before relying on a non-pinned flag.\n54: \n55: <!-- /ANCHOR:installation -->\n56: \n57: <!-- ANCHOR:subcommand-map -->\n58: ## 3. SUBCOMMAND MAP\n59: \n60: OpenCode exposes a multi-subcommand surface. The cli-opencode skill primarily invokes `run`, with secondary use of `serve`, `web`, `agent`, and `debug`.\n61: \n62: | Subcommand | Purpose | Invoked by cli-opencode |\n63: |------------|---------|-------------------------|\n64: | `opencode` (default) | Start the TUI in the current project | No (interactive only) |\n65: | `opencode run [message..]` | Non-interactive single-shot dispatch | YES (canonical use case) |\n66: | `opencode serve` | Start a headless server | YES (for parallel detached sessions) |\n67: | `opencode web` | Start a server plus open the web interface | YES (when the operator wants a browser surface) |\n68: | `opencode acp` | Start an ACP (Agent Client Protocol) server | No (specialized integration path) |\n69: | `opencode attach <url>` | Attach to a running OpenCode server | YES (for share-URL flows) |\n70: | `opencode agent` | Manage agent definitions | YES (for agent listing) |\n71: | `opencode debug` | Debugging and troubleshooting tools | YES (for `debug skill` and `debug agent` listings) |\n72: | `opencode mcp` | Manage MCP server registrations | No |\n73: | `opencode providers` (alias `auth`) | Manage AI providers and credentials | No (operator-driven setup) |\n74: | `opencode models [provider]` | List available models | YES (for capability discovery) |\n75: | `opencode session` | Manage sessions | No (state inspection only) |\n76: | `opencode export [sessionID]` | Export session data as JSON | YES (for memory handback flows) |\n77: | `opencode stats` | Token and cost statistics | No |\n78: | `opencode db` | Database tools | No |\n79: | `opencode plugin <module>` (alias `plug`) | Install a plugin | No (operator-driven setup) |\n80: | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Upgrade the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 295. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\ndescription: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n\nComprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\nOpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n\n### Purpose\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","time":{"start":1777215874209,"end":1777215874223}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215876320,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca5225d8001ql0sNgg15pEBYi","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_x3LD3GMlYS1ssEXtSch5cSPV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\n3: description: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n7: \n8: How cli-opencode positions itself relative to the four sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: The four sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n16: \n17: cli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n18: \n19: | Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n20: |----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|\n21: | 1. External runtime to OpenCode | Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, raw shell | OpenCode for full plugin / skill / MCP runtime | No |\n22: | 2. In-OpenCode parallel detached session | OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp) | New OpenCode session via `--share --port N` | No (different session id) |\n23: | 3. Cross-AI orchestration handback | Codex / Copilot / Gemini | OpenCode for spec-kit specific workflows | No |\n24: \n25: The cycle ADR-001 protects against is the operator inside OpenCode asking cli-opencode to \"delegate this exact prompt to OpenCode\" — that case is REFUSED at the routing layer.\n26: \n27: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n28: \n29: <!-- ANCHOR:use-case-1 -->\n30: ## 2. USE CASE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE\n31: \n32: ### When to use\n33: \n34: The calling AI is Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, or a raw shell. The task needs the project's full plugin / skill / MCP / Spec Kit Memory runtime — not just a raw model dispatch. Examples:\n35: \n36: - Run `memory_search` against the project's spec-doc database\n37: - Call CocoIndex for semantic code search across the repo\n38: - Dispatch a `@deep-research` or `@deep-review` agent loop with externalized state\n39: - Run a sub-agent that needs Spec Kit Memory for continuity across iterations\n40: \n41: ### Smart-router signal\n42: \n43: ADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (no OPENCODE_* env var, no opencode parent process, no live state lock).\n44: \n45: ### Prompt template\n46: \n47: ```text\n48: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n49: \n50: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n51: \n52: Context:\n53: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n54: - Plugins / skills required: <list>\n55: - MCP tools required: <list>\n56: \n57: Constraints:\n58: - <list>\n59: \n60: Success criteria:\n61: - <list>\n62: \n63: Memory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end of the response so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n64: ```\n65: \n66: ### Invocation shape\n67: \n68: ```bash\n69: opencode run \\\n70:   --model opencode-go/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n71:   --agent general \\\n72:   --variant high \\\n73:   --format json \\\n74:   --dir /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public \\\n75:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n76: ```\n77: \n78: ### Why it matters\n79: \n80: This is the canonical cross-AI dispatch path. It gives external runtimes a one-shot bridge into the project's full runtime without forcing the operator to leave their host session.\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 323. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\ndescription: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n\nHow cli-opencode positions itself relative to the four sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe four sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n\ncli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n\n| Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n|----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","time":{"start":1777215876306,"end":1777215876318}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215878433,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca522e10001Q3CRninpFJwmWb","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_02_pGOgL62eCkWvUxqk4US4W5Rj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/opencode_tools.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/opencode_tools.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Unique Capabilities and Comparison\"\n3: description: \"Documents the value props that distinguish opencode run from raw model dispatch — full plugin/skill/MCP runtime context, parallel detached sessions, structured event stream, agent dispatch, and cross-repo working directory routing.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode CLI - Unique Capabilities\n7: \n8: What `opencode run` brings that the four sibling cli-* dispatches do not. Each capability includes the invocation shape and the use case where it pays off.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: The four sibling cli-* skills (cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-copilot, cli-gemini) dispatch a raw model behind a thin CLI wrapper. The model loads no project context, no plugins, no skills, no MCP tools, and no Spec Kit Memory unless the calling AI manually attaches files or pastes context.\n16: \n17: `opencode run` is different. It spawns a full OpenCode session. That session loads:\n18: \n19: 1. Every plugin registered in the project's `opencode.json`\n20: 2. Every skill under `.opencode/skill/`\n21: 3. Every MCP tool wired through `opencode.json` and `.utcp_config.json`\n22: 4. The full Spec Kit Memory MCP database\n23: 5. The project's CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md instructions\n24: 6. The structural code graph and CocoIndex semantic index\n25: \n26: The cli-opencode skill exists because no sibling provides this. It is the bridge between an external AI and the full plugin / skill / MCP runtime this repo defines.\n27: \n28: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n29: \n30: <!-- ANCHOR:capability-1 -->\n31: ## 2. FULL PLUGIN, SKILL, AND MCP RUNTIME\n32: \n33: ### What it does\n34: \n35: When `opencode run` starts a session, the runtime loads every plugin, skill, and MCP server the project configures. The dispatched agent has access to:\n36: \n37: - All `Skill` invocations the calling AI has access to (system-spec-kit, sk-doc, sk-code-opencode, etc.)\n38: - All MCP tools (Spec Kit Memory's 40+ tools, CocoIndex semantic search, Code Mode for ClickUp / Figma / Webflow, sequential thinking)\n39: - Every project-local plugin\n40: - The repo's CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md instruction set as the system prompt\n41: \n42: ### Why it matters\n43: \n44: A Claude Code CLI dispatch via `claude -p \"<prompt>\"` runs raw Claude with no plugins and no MCP. To get the same plugin / skill / MCP context inside Claude Code the operator would need to run a TUI session and import the project — not a one-shot invocation.\n45: \n46: `opencode run` is the only one-shot path that loads the full runtime.\n47: \n48: ### Invocation shape\n49: \n50: ```bash\n51: opencode run \\\n52:   --model opencode-go/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n53:   --agent general \\\n54:   --variant high \\\n55:   --format json \\\n56:   --dir /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public \\\n57:   \"Analyze the spec-kit memory database health using memory_health, then propose three improvements with concrete file:line citations.\"\n58: ```\n59: \n60: The dispatched session loads `system-spec-kit` skill, calls `memory_health` (an MCP tool), inspects the database, and writes the proposal back through Spec Kit Memory's normal save pipeline.\n61: \n62: <!-- /ANCHOR:capability-1 -->\n63: \n64: <!-- ANCHOR:capability-2 -->\n65: ## 3. PARALLEL DETACHED SESSIONS\n66: \n67: ### What it does\n68: \n69: A second `opencode run --share --port <N>` invocation from inside an existing OpenCode session spawns a separate session with its own session id, its own state directory, and a publishable share URL. The original session continues unaffected.\n70: \n71: ### Why it matters\n72: \n73: For ablation suites, worker farms, and parallel research sweeps, the operator wants N sessions running concurrently. Each session must have:\n74: \n75: - A unique session id (not a fork of the parent)\n76: - An independent state directory (no shared `messages.jsonl`)\n77: - An optional share URL so the operator can inspect it from a browser\n78: - The same plugin / skill / MCP runtime as the parent\n79: \n80: ### Invocation shape\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 207. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Unique Capabilities and Comparison\"\ndescription: \"Documents the value props that distinguish opencode run from raw model dispatch — full plugin/skill/MCP runtime context, parallel detached sessions, structured event stream, agent dispatch, and cross-repo working directory routing.\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Unique Capabilities\n\nWhat `opencode run` brings that the four sibling cli-* dispatches do not. Each capability includes the invocation shape and the use case where it pays off.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe four sibling cli-* skills (cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-copilot, cli-gemini) dispatch a raw model behind a thin CLI wrapper. The model loads no project context, no plugins, no skills, no MCP tools, and no Spec Kit Memory unless the calling AI manually attaches files or pastes context.\n\n`opencode run` is different. It spawns a full OpenCode session. That session loads:\n\n1. Every plugin registered in the project's `opencode.json`\n2. Every skill under `.opencode/skill/`","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/opencode_tools.md","time":{"start":1777215878426,"end":1777215878432}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215880543,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca523656001H95vRXOhYgu8so","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_03_xLxA1gOy7dj7XIqFC1VFbxGI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/agent_delegation.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/agent_delegation.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Agent Delegation\"\n3: description: \"Agent routing matrix for opencode run dispatches. Documents the agent slugs available via .opencode/agent/, the cli pattern As @<agent> for prompt-time routing, and the orchestration principle: calling AI decides WHAT, agent shapes HOW.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode CLI - Agent Delegation\n7: \n8: How cli-opencode routes dispatches to specialized OpenCode agents via the `--agent <slug>` flag. The calling AI decides WHAT to delegate. The agent's frontmatter shapes HOW the dispatched session processes it.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: OpenCode agents are markdown files under `.opencode/agent/<slug>.md`. Each file's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, system prompt, and behavioral constraints. When `opencode run --agent <slug>` is invoked, the dispatched session inherits all of that.\n16: \n17: The cli-opencode skill exposes the project's full agent roster. The calling AI selects the right slug based on the task type. The agent then shapes the dispatched session — different model, different tool permissions, different system prompt.\n18: \n19: ### Discovery commands\n20: \n21: | Command | Purpose |\n22: |---------|---------|\n23: | `opencode agent list` | List all registered agent slugs across project + user scopes |\n24: | `opencode debug agent <slug>` | Print resolved frontmatter and system prompt for a slug |\n25: | `opencode debug skill <slug>` | Print skill resolution if the agent loads one |\n26: \n27: Project-local agents resolve from `.opencode/agent/<slug>.md`. User-level agents fall back from `~/.opencode/agent/<slug>.md` when the project file is missing. The `debug agent` subcommand prints the merged result so the calling AI can confirm which file the dispatch will load.\n28: \n29: ### Orchestration principle\n30: \n31: The calling AI decides WHAT to delegate. The agent's frontmatter shapes HOW the dispatched session processes the task. The calling AI always validates and integrates the output.\n32: \n33: This separation of concerns is load-bearing for the cli-opencode skill: the calling AI owns the task graph and the integration step, while the dispatched OpenCode session owns the per-task execution under the agent's tool permissions and system prompt.\n34: \n35: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n36: \n37: <!-- ANCHOR:orchestration-model -->\n38: ## 2. ORCHESTRATION MODEL\n39: \n40: ```text\n41: Calling AI (CONDUCTOR)\n42:   |\n43:   |-- Analyzes task, selects OpenCode agent slug\n44:   |-- Constructs opencode run command with --agent <slug> flag\n45:   |-- Delegates via Bash tool\n46:   |\n47:   v\n48: opencode run --agent <slug> (EXECUTOR ENTRY)\n49:   |\n50:   |-- Resolves .opencode/agent/<slug>.md frontmatter\n51:   |-- Pins model, tool permissions, system prompt, behavioral rules\n52:   |-- Loads project plugins, skills, and MCP servers\n53:   |\n54:   v\n55: OpenCode Session (AGENT EXECUTION)\n56:   |\n57:   |-- Agent shapes the dispatch under its frontmatter constraints\n58:   |-- Streams JSON events (session.started, message.delta, tool.call,\n59:   |    tool.result, session.completed) to the calling AI\n60:   |-- Honors LEAF agent restrictions (no nested dispatches, read-only)\n61:   |\n62:   v\n63: Calling AI (CONDUCTOR — RESULT HANDBACK)\n64:   |\n65:   |-- Parses the JSON event stream\n66:   |-- Validates agent output quality\n67:   |-- Integrates findings into the parent workflow\n68:   |-- Decides next step (next dispatch, completion, escalation)\n69: ```\n70: \n71: ### Invocation pattern\n72: \n73: cli-opencode dispatches use the `--agent <slug>` flag. The flag loads the agent definition from `.opencode/agent/<slug>.md` (project-local) or the user-level fallback. The dispatch shape pins model, variant, format, and working directory alongside the agent slug:\n74: \n75: ```bash\n76: opencode run \\\n77:   --model opencode-go/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n78:   --agent <slug> \\\n79:   --variant high \\\n80:   --format json \\\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 445. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Agent Delegation\"\ndescription: \"Agent routing matrix for opencode run dispatches. Documents the agent slugs available via .opencode/agent/, the cli pattern As @<agent> for prompt-time routing, and the orchestration principle: calling AI decides WHAT, agent shapes HOW.\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Agent Delegation\n\nHow cli-opencode routes dispatches to specialized OpenCode agents via the `--agent <slug>` flag. The calling AI decides WHAT to delegate. The agent's frontmatter shapes HOW the dispatched session processes it.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nOpenCode agents are markdown files under `.opencode/agent/<slug>.md`. Each file's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, system prompt, and behavioral constraints. When `opencode run --agent <slug>` is invoked, the dispatched session inherits all of that.\n\nThe cli-opencode skill exposes the project's full agent roster. The calling AI selects the right slug based on the task type. The agent then shapes the dispatched session — different model, different tool permissions, different system prompt.\n\n### Discovery commands\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/references/agent_delegation.md","time":{"start":1777215880528,"end":1777215880541}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215882592,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca523e8800188sQbLrFAXkb2N","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_04_0CBP8e12T5iQ6vJoP5mcJyDS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Prompt Templates\"\n3: description: \"Copy-paste ready prompt templates for the three documented use cases plus specialized agent dispatch, parallel detached sessions, ablation suites, worker farms, cross-AI handback, and Memory Epilogue.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OpenCode CLI - Prompt Templates\n7: \n8: Copy-paste templates for `opencode run` dispatches. Each template names the use case it serves, the framework it applies, and the canonical invocation shape.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: The cli-opencode skill ships templates for the three documented use cases (per ADR-002) plus specialized dispatches for agent routing, parallel research, ablation, worker farms, and cross-AI handback. Every template ends with the Memory Epilogue when the calling AI needs to preserve session context.\n16: \n17: Templates are numbered for cross-reference from `references/integration_patterns.md` and `SKILL.md`.\n18: \n19: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n20: \n21: <!-- ANCHOR:template-1 -->\n22: ## 2. TEMPLATE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE (USE CASE 1)\n23: \n24: **Framework:** RCAF\n25: **Calling runtime:** Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, raw shell\n26: \n27: ```text\n28: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n29: \n30: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n31: \n32: Context:\n33: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n34: - Plugins / skills required: <list>\n35: - MCP tools required: <list>\n36: \n37: Constraints:\n38: - <list>\n39: \n40: Success criteria:\n41: - <list>\n42: \n43: Memory Epilogue:\n44: At the end of your response, include a structured handback inside delimiters:\n45: \n46: <!-- MEMORY_HANDBACK_START -->\n47: {\n48:   \"specFolder\": \"<path>\",\n49:   \"sessionSummary\": \"<one-paragraph summary>\",\n50:   \"user_prompts\": [\"<verbatim prompt>\"],\n51:   \"observations\": [\"<key finding 1>\", \"<key finding 2>\"],\n52:   \"recent_context\": [\"<recent change 1>\"],\n53:   \"FILES\": [\n54:     {\"path\": \"<path>\", \"DESCRIPTION\": \"<change description>\", \"ACTION\": \"<verb>\", \"MODIFICATION_MAGNITUDE\": \"<small|medium|large>\"}\n55:   ],\n56:   \"nextSteps\": [\"<next safe action>\"]\n57: }\n58: <!-- MEMORY_HANDBACK_END -->\n59: ```\n60: \n61: ```bash\n62: opencode run \\\n63:   --model opencode-go/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n64:   --agent general \\\n65:   --variant high \\\n66:   --format json \\\n67:   --dir /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public \\\n68:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n69: ```\n70: \n71: <!-- /ANCHOR:template-1 -->\n72: \n73: <!-- ANCHOR:template-2 -->\n74: ## 3. TEMPLATE 2 — IN-OPENCODE PARALLEL DETACHED SESSION (USE CASE 2)\n75: \n76: **Framework:** CIDI\n77: **Calling runtime:** OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp)\n78: \n79: ```text\n80: You are spawning a parallel detached OpenCode session for <purpose>.\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 496. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Prompt Templates\"\ndescription: \"Copy-paste ready prompt templates for the three documented use cases plus specialized agent dispatch, parallel detached sessions, ablation suites, worker farms, cross-AI handback, and Memory Epilogue.\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Prompt Templates\n\nCopy-paste templates for `opencode run` dispatches. Each template names the use case it serves, the framework it applies, and the canonical invocation shape.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe cli-opencode skill ships templates for the three documented use cases (per ADR-002) plus specialized dispatches for agent routing, parallel research, ablation, worker farms, and cross-AI handback. Every template ends with the Memory Epilogue when the calling AI needs to preserve session context.\n\nTemplates are numbered for cross-reference from `references/integration_patterns.md` and `SKILL.md`.\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md","time":{"start":1777215882574,"end":1777215882590}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777215884684,"sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","part":{"id":"prt_dca524687001HEnb64NXTmayKB","messageID":"msg_dca5207e2001jNMySKKE6LaqvQ","sessionID":"ses_235ae4ddfffeslQpORMPty8nFN","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_05_KmG7o0GoAKjwdWSNd8GpsLCl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Prompt Quality Card\n3: description: Fast-path framework selection and CLEAR checks for OpenCode CLI prompt construction.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: <!-- sync: 9d3a5fd2 -->\n7: \n8: # Prompt Quality Card\n9: \n10: Fast-path prompt-quality guidance for OpenCode CLI dispatches. Use this asset before building a routine `opencode run` prompt so the router stays lightweight while still applying framework selection and a quick CLEAR pass.\n11: \n12: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n13: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n14: \n15: ### Purpose\n16: \n17: Provide a small, always-load asset for OpenCode CLI prompt construction that improves quality without pulling in the full prompt-engineering skill on routine dispatches.\n18: \n19: ### Usage\n20: \n21: Select a framework from the task map, run the CLEAR 5-check, and escalate to `@improve-prompt` when the task crosses the fast-path risk threshold.\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n26: <!-- ANCHOR:framework-selection-table -->\n27: ## 2. Framework Selection Table\n28: \n29: | Framework | Best for | Complexity band | Core components |\n30: |-----------|----------|-----------------|-----------------|\n31: | `RCAF` | General implementation, edit, and documentation prompts | 1-6 | Role, Context, Action, Format |\n32: | `COSTAR` | Audience-aware communication and content generation | 3-6 | Context, Objective, Style, Tone, Audience, Response |\n33: | `RACE` | Fast single-output tasks where speed matters most | 1-3 | Role, Action, Context, Execute |\n34: | `CIDI` | Process instructions, tutorials, and SOP-style prompts | 4-6 | Context, Instructions, Details, Input |\n35: | `TIDD-EC` | Compliance, review, and quality-critical prompts | 6-8 | Task, Instructions, Do's, Don'ts, Examples, Context |\n36: | `CRISPE` | Research, strategic exploration, and option generation | 5-7 | Capacity, Insight, Statement, Personality, Experiment |\n37: | `CRAFT` | Complex multi-stakeholder planning and analysis | 7-10 | Context, Role, Action, Format, Target |\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: <!-- /ANCHOR:framework-selection-table -->\n42: <!-- ANCHOR:task-framework-map -->\n43: ## 3. Task to Framework Map\n44: \n45: | Task | Framework |\n46: |------|-----------|\n47: | Generation | `RCAF` |\n48: | Review | `TIDD-EC` |\n49: | Research | `CRISPE` |\n50: | Edit | `RCAF + TIDD-EC` |\n51: | Analyze / plan | `CRAFT` |\n52: | Parallel detached session (use case 2) | `CIDI` |\n53: | Cross-AI handback (use case 3) | `RCAF + TIDD-EC` |\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: <!-- /ANCHOR:task-framework-map -->\n58: <!-- ANCHOR:clear-check -->\n59: ## 4. CLEAR 5-Check\n60: \n61: - Correctness: Does the prompt describe the real task and files without contradiction?\n62: - Logic: Does it explain how the dispatched OpenCode session should reason or decide?\n63: - Expression: Is the wording specific enough to avoid guesswork?\n64: - Arrangement: Is the order task -> context -> constraints -> output -> verification?\n65: - Reusability: Could this prompt be reused by swapping placeholders?\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: <!-- /ANCHOR:clear-check -->\n70: <!-- ANCHOR:escalation -->\n71: ## 5. Escalate to `@improve-prompt`\n72: \n73: Use Task-based escalation when complexity is `>= 7/10`, compliance or security sensitivity appears, more than one stakeholder matters, or more than one requirement is unclear.\n74: \n75: OpenCode-specific example: if the task would otherwise need a long `opencode run` prompt plus an explicit Memory Epilogue and a parallel-session decision, ask `@improve-prompt` for the final `ENHANCED_PROMPT` first and then pass that result to OpenCode.\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: <!-- /ANCHOR:escalation -->\n80: <!-- ANCHOR:failure-patterns -->\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 101. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Prompt Quality Card\ndescription: Fast-path framework selection and CLEAR checks for OpenCode CLI prompt construction.\n---\n\n<!-- sync: 9d3a5fd2 -->\n\n# Prompt Quality Card\n\nFast-path prompt-quality guidance for OpenCode CLI dispatches. Use this asset before building a routine `opencode run` prompt so the router stays lightweight while still applying framework selection and a quick CLEAR pass.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvide a small, always-load asset for OpenCode CLI prompt construction that improves quality without pulling in the full prompt-engineering skill on routine dispatches.\n\n### Usage\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skill/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","time":{"start":1777215884674,"end":1777215884683}}}}
